    Preamble

The GNU General Public License is a free, copyleft license for software
and other kinds of works.

The licenses for most software are designed to take away your freedom to
share and change it. By contrast, the GNU General Public License is
intended to guarantee your freedom to share and change all versions of
a program—to make sure it remains free software for all its users.

When we speak of free software, we are referring to freedom, not
price. Our General Public Licenses are designed to make sure that you
have the freedom to distribute copies of free software (and charge for
them if you wish), that you receive source code or can get it if you
want it, that you can change the software and share your changes with
others, and that you know you can do these things.

To protect your rights, we need to make restrictions that forbid
you to deprive others of these rights. Therefore, you have to abide
by the terms of the GPL if you distribute copies of the software, or
if you modify it. 

For example, if you distribute copies of such a program,
you must pass on the same freedoms to the recipients that you
received. You must make sure that they, too, receive or can get the
source code. And you must show them these terms so they know their
rights.

We protect your rights with two steps: (1) copy this license
and (2) add some information about who owns the copyright and
who gives out this license.  Also, for each author's protection
we want to make sure that everyone understands that there is no
warranty for this free software.  If the software is modified
by someone else and passed on, we want its recipients to know
that what they have is not the original, so that any problems
introduced by others will not reflect on the original authors' reputations.

    1.  Source Code.

The source code for a work means the preferred form of the work for
making modifications to it.  It is a common convention to make the
source code available in a standardized form that is suitable for
modification.  A program is only a derivative of another if it can
be modified or changed into it; that is, if it is the same kind of
work as the original or can easily be combined with it.

    2.  Basic Permissions.

You may use the Program under the terms of this License.
You will be able to run it for all practical purposes and you can
take the Program, copy it, and distribute it, give it to anyone,
look at it, change it, and improve it, and distribute copies of your
modified versions.

For the practical purposes of this License, any arrangement to
make the Program available to the public, such as the practice of
making it available on the Internet, is a form of distribution.

In addition, you can do so only if you pass on the same freedoms
that you received.

    3.  Copyleft.

This is a key aspect of the GPL: when you distribute copies or
you modify the software, you must pass on the same freedoms that
you received.  This means that you can not make a closed-source
version of this software; all copies and derivative works
must stay open-source.  This can be somewhat confusing, so we
include some examples of how this works in practice.

    4.  Surrendering Rights.

You are not allowed to surrender any of your rights under this
License.

    5.  Disclaimer of Warranty.

There is no warranty for this free software.  Column III of the
ordinary GPL gives you a certain warranty and almost all
options require a warranty, however, as you are able to make
any arbitrary action with this free software,
there is no warranty.

    6.  Termination.

If you do not abide by the terms of this License, all rights
which are granted to you under this License shall terminate
instantly.  However, if you do abide by this License, your
rights continue.

If you wish to integrate this license into your own software,
you need to finalize the terms of your contract with FSF.
(There are some other licenses, such as the Lesser GPL and the
Apache License, which allow integrating open-source software.
Check the FSF website for more information on how to integrate
your software.)

